deck_description: Always try to go first turn with this deck, because synchro summons can be easily stopped by set cards. When you have a good hand, this deck is capable of bringing out cosmic blazar dragon, in the only condition that you know synchro monsters very well and do know how to use a synchro deck. If cosmic blazar is not possible, always try to bring out crystal wing, clear wing, or shooting star. A few tips: 1. cosmic blazar is impossible to summon if there are no level eaters in the graveyard. 2: Stardust dragon is very weak by itself, so always use it to bring out shooting star. 3: Synchro is history. So don't be surprised if a meta deck beat you easily.

deck_excerpt: True Draco and  Metalfoes combine to make a competitive deck that will stand against the ever-changing meta.
deck_description: This deck is pretty simple to use and get the hang of. It uses the Draco engine and metalfoes for support to pendulum summon the draco's or fuse them to provide support or small draw power. Metalfoes Mythriel is your ace fusion as it helps you recycle your metalfoes in the deck and uses you the opportunity to return a troublesome monster card back to the hand or extra deck. Other fusions are there for support and different options. A variety of different Xyz to help balance the extra deck and to use in sticky situations.  Ash Blossom can be used to stop the drawing of cards which could bring a problem going into other meta decks that use a lot of draw power. Metalfoes fusion stays at 2 just in case it gets banished and it can recycle itself for a draw so its never a bad choice. This deck has been used against all aspects of non-link meta and has done very well against them all. (Link will be added later on to update deck use)

deck_excerpt: Unleash the power of Obelisk and Slifer by summoning Super Quantum and Quickdraw support, and make them invincible through Mound of the Bound Creator
deck_description:
This Deck's concept is very simple: Summoning an Egyptian God should be a problem for your opponent, in particular if this God cannot be taken down by effects. The most annoying problem of Egyptian Gods is that their Summon is quite slow, as you need 3 monsters to Tribute: this can be resolved with some not so new cards and combos. Main combo families:
  • Super Quantum is the newest tactic I added into this Deck for its easy-to-use and Cyber Dragon-alike style: since Red Layer and Blue Layer can recall each other from Deck or GY, they make really very easy for us to gain the 3 monsters we need to Summon an Egyptian God; in addition, there are many XYZs to Summon if you - for example - don't have any Egyptian God in your hand or that Summon wouldn't be so useful for the play.
  • Quickdraw Synchron, Level Eater & Inferno Reckless Summon are an old-school set that fulls your board with monsters you can use to Synchro Summon some of the classic Yusei Fudo's heroes or to Summon an Egyptian God.
  • Nimble Momonga & Giant Rat are a good defensive strategy if you stuck in a bad situation and you run out of Traps or powerful monsters.
  • Hardened Armed Dragon & Mound of the Bound Creator are to support cards that power up your Egyptian Gods so that they become unaffected by card effects.
The Extra Deck is often used as a plan B, so it contains very strong and bossy XYZs and, on the other hand, some good Synchros; to be honest, I've never actually tested the Link monsters in the Side, but I'm confident those are quite good.

deck_excerpt: A powerful WATER-based deck that focuses on using cards such as Legendary Fisherman III, White Aura Biphamet and Stronghold Whale.
deck_description:
The focus of the deck is to summon out your boss monsters as soon as possible. The deck considers the following monsters to be "boss mosnters" => Legendary Fisherman III, White Aura Biphamet, White Aura Whale, Stronghold Whale and Poseidra the Atlantean Dragon. These monsters are then protected mainly by Sea Stealth Attack. Some general combos for the deck:
  1. The Legendary Fisherman II + A Legendary Ocean = The Legendary Fisherman III.
  2. Instant Fusion Sea Monster of Theseus + Level 4 (with A Legendary Ocean on the field) = White Aura Dolphin.
  3. Deep Sea Diva => SS Fishborg Launcher or Legendary Atlantean Tridon (with a Legendary Ocean) = Tatsunoko. If you then have a Level 7 in your hand = White Aura Biphamet.
  4. Sea Stealth Attack can Banish an Instant Fusion target and keep it alive after the end phase.
  5. Instant Fusion into Rare Fish can lead to some Rank 4 XYZ plays.
  6. Foolish Burial can be used on Stronghold Whale to SS it from the Graveyard if you have two WATER monsters on the field. This can be particularly useful if you are in urgent need of a Sea Stealth Attack.
  7. Remember! Sea Stealth Attack can be used to effectively protect your monsters from removal, use it! And do not forget about its secondary effect to instantly destroy an opponents monster in battle if you are battling with a Level 5 or higher (and thankfully it's original level of 5 or higher so A Legendary Ocean doesn't impact on this secondary effect).

deck_excerpt: Shaddoll + Lightsworn + Sephylon = Yummy
deck_description:
This deck has multiple win conditions.

Obviously, this deck has a huge set of Shaddoll's, so that's the main premise. Sadly, El Shaddoll Construct is banned, so this is the best build in order to go around it, in my opinion. With this deck, there are multiple extra tech's that can help you out when things aren't going your way and your monsters are being destroyed quickly.
The purpose of this deck is primarily to beat down your opponent so you can win with the powerful Shaddoll's and the multitude of Synchro/XYZ Monsters in the extra deck. All these can give you an out to many decks you may face. The Lightsworn Monsters exist from the old deck in which I ran El Shaddoll Construct, but since its ban, I decided to add in Sephylon, The Ultimate Timelord to the mix. I know, replacing an Extra Deck Monster with a Main Deck Monster seems dumb, but listen on. Sephylon needs to be special summoned from your hand by having 10 or more monsters in the Graveyard. Now luckily, Shaddoll's have a useful effect when sent to the Graveyard by card effects, so that helps us with him. In addition to that, the Lightsworn's Raiden & Lyla & the Spell Card Charge of the Light Brigade add some more spiciness to this deck because Raiden can help to get monsters in the Graveyard AND activate effects of the Shaddoll's if they get discarded this way, and Lyla can destroy Spells/Traps that the opponent has either face-down or activated (such as continuous spells/traps or field spells), then she sends more Monsters from the deck to the grave once the turn has ended, hopefully spitting out more Shaddoll's. When the Lightsworn's send Monsters to the Graveyard, a mix of Light & Dark Monsters may lay there, so, the BLS - EotB and the Chaos Sorcerer are there in order to benefit from these. They both have effects to just straight up destroy other Monsters, and they're tough to get by. I've added Rainbow Kuriboh to stop your Opponent's Monsters from attacking, along with Vanity's Fiend, since Vanity's Emptiness is banned. These aren't only extra Monsters for Sephylon, but also extra Light & Dark's for BLS & Chaos Sorcerer.

Frightfur Patchwork is there to search Polymerization and Edge Imp Sabres.

Dragostapelia can negate your oponent's monsters effects by putting a Predator counter on them. You can use your opponent's monsters as Dark type materials with Chlamydosundew to make further Fusions.

Scapeghost summons multiple tokens that you can use to Fusion Summon Predaplant Triphyovertum or Dragonecro Nethersoul Dragon

Fusion Recycling Plant  is a strong Field spell card to use on this deck. You will use it most of the times to add  a Chlamydosundew that was used as a Fusion material via its effect to make further Fusion Summons.

  Updated as 8/5/2020

deck_excerpt: Spam rank 10s & run over your opponent with these trains.
deck_description: The deck has been slowed down significantly since links, but here it is. Monsters: Express Knight & Derricrane are your main combo pieces with Ruffian Railcar helping to support that combo. (also the field spell helps you get to one or the other) We also run a Kaiju engine with Jizukiru being a level 10 Machine that synergizes with the deck nicely. Exodius is cool for recycling & Cyber End Dragon for another level 10(can't forget Maxx C). Spells: Switchyard is the field spell we need, you can special summon Ruffian off its 1st effect & it changes to a level 10, but you can't deal battle damage to your opponent when you do so. The 2nd effect is what we want, you can pitch a card to the grave & add one of your level 10 trains to your hand. Running 3 Terraforming is essential & scapegoats for links. Now for the on-of list, most are self-explanatory. Raigeki, Kaiju Slumber, Upstart, soul charge, Limiter Removal for otk & Foolish Burial for pitching Ruffian. Also running Skill Drain. For the extra deck, you mostly go into Super Dora & sometimes Gustav Max for burn. Skypalace is pretty situational. Galaxy Destroyer is hilarious if you get his effect off & for wiping the back row & popping pendulum scales. Number 35 & 84 work great together& we finish off with our Link monsters.

deck_excerpt: Fun HERO deck focusing on its fusions and Masked HERO monsters rather than just Dark Law and Toadally Awesome!
deck_description: This is a HERO deck build around its fusions, not just around Dark Law & Toadally Awesome! My usual opening is with Elemental HERO Nova Master & Elemental HERO Absolute Zero on the field and an Elemental HERO Honesty Neos in the hand (with something else as well) and possibly a face down, depending on starting first or second. After that, if Absolute Zero is killed it blows up your opponents monsters and if Nova Master is attacked, send Honesty Neos to the GY to boost him to 5100 ATK (beating Utopia the Lightning if you activate it before the battle phase) and then you can draw a card. If the facedown is a Change spell, you can also change Absolute Zero into Acid and wipe out your opponents board (It feels good) Thats just one of many strategies. For draw power you've got Nova Master, Divine Wind, Legacy of a Hero & Supply Squad. Its a fun deck, feel free to make any changes and have fun with it.

deck_excerpt: SHIRANUI/GANDORA OTK
deck_description:
So far, the "Shiranui" monsters have effects that basically revolve around providing card advantage when they are banished.

The non-Tuner Main Deck monsters have a set of two very versatile effects: the first one ranges from the set-up of Synchro/Xyz Summons to a boost on offensiveness; the second one triggers when they are banished and ranges from card retrieving to card destruction. "Shiranui Spectralsword" is currently the only Tuner of the archetype and allows the player to Special Summon a Zombie-Type Synchro Monster from the Extra Deck, by banishing itself alongside with a non-Tuner Zombie-Type monster, both from the Graveyard. Although this Special Summon is not treated as a Synchro Summon, this effect allows the player to unleash monsters that would normally require specific Synchro Materials, notably "Archfiend Zombie-Skull". There are currently three boss monsters in the Archetype, all of them being Synchro Monsters: "Shiranui Samuraisaga", "Shiranui Shogunsaga" and "Shiranui Sunsaga". "Shiranui Samuraisaga" can recycle one of your banished "Shiranui" monsters and then restrain the opponent's aggression; if it ends up being banished, it can weaken one opposing monster's ATK by 500 points. "Shiranui Shogunsaga" has higher stats and a more straightforward set of effects: when it is Special Summoned by any means, it can banish one Zombie-Type monster from the Graveyard in order to raise its 3000 base ATK by an amount equal to the banished monster's ATK; this effect is obviously more powerful when its target is a "Shiranui" monster, that will have its second effect triggered. When it is destroyed, its owner can return one of their banished Zombies with 0 DEF to the Graveyard. "Shiranui Sunsaga" has the highest ATK of the group, at 3500. It's summon effect allows it to recycle any number of Zombie-Type Synchro monsters, banished or in the Graveyard, back into the Extra deck, then destroying cards the opponent controls up to the number of cards recycled by this effect. Its main power comes from its destruction negation, as it can prevent the destruction of any Zombie-type monster (by battle or card effect) by banishing a "Shiranui" monster from the graveyard, saving your monsters and activating the banished monstered effect. Each boss monster is two levels higher than the previous boss, allowing the effect of "Shiranui Spectralsword" to special summon the next boss monster should the previous one be destroyed. LETS GO OVER THE 3 GANDORA'S  their main effects banish and destroy cards while offering a atk boost but at a price. it halves your lp. but clears the field. giga is easy to summon (2 tributes from hand or field) while the others need tributes. to prevent bricking from high lvl cards i use montage dragon. heres how i go about this deck. i use the grass looks greener to throw cards into the gy. youll notice that most of the cards have effects that activate when sent to the gy. this is the decks main defense and summon engine. while i wait for that... ill summon two level 4 monsters with mezuki, fairytail or a shiranuis effect. (fairy-tail and pot of desire will also help power giga-rays when the time comes) and special summon bagooska to give me time. and help set the field while offering effect negates. this is when i set cards like peropero or electroturtle if they are in hand. after a couple turns of throwing cards into the grave and banish pile. i use spectralsword or anothers effect to special summon the higher lvl shiranui and keep that going to test and clear the field. just gage it from there. once you hit that point its extremly easy to spam the field. phantom chaos is in the deck to futher trigger gigas effect. other than that have fun. hope you guys like the deck!   this is for the pc (og) version so i follow the banlist. but for mobile players (ygopro) add 2 more copies of the grass looks greener and take out a unizombie and book of life and youre set.

deck_excerpt: A deck based around Deskbots. That's about it.
deck_description:
Intro to the cards

The usual main attackers are Deskbot 001, Deskbot 004, Deskbot 007, Deskbot 008, and Deskbot 009. The support cards are Deskbot 002, Deskbot 003, Deskbot 005, Deskbot 006, and Deskbot Jet. All of the Deskbots, if they have the proper setup, can deal heavy damage. The four Pendulum Monsters are Deskbot 005, 006, 007, and 008. 007 and 008 are more attack based because their effects are aimed at them getting damage in. 005 and 006 are better for Pendulum Summoning and their effects are aimed at getting more Deskbots onto the field. Deskbot Jet is the Synchro Monster. It has two effects that can be activated, but only once per turn, and once that turn. It also has it's normal effect which boosts its power. The Field Spell, Deskbot Base, is sometimes annoying, sometimes helpful. It can boost all Deskbot monsters on the fields Attack and Defense by 500. This can ruin part of the strategy. It's more useful effects are as follows: Once per turn: You can reveal any number of "Deskbot" cards in your hand and shuffle them into the Deck, then draw the same number of cards. You can banish 9 "Deskbot" cards with different names from your field and/or Graveyard, except "Deskbot Base"; shuffle all cards from your opponent's hand, field and Graveyard into the Deck. The more useful out of the useful effects is shuffling and drawing cards. It can help refresh a bad hand. The other effect is situational.

How to play them

  I'm going to show you a combo I love to use with this deck. The ideal hand is as follows (If you are going first); Machine Duplication, Deskbot 003, Deskbot 005/006, Bottomless Trap Hole/Raigeki/Twin Twisters, and Deskbot 009. Place Deskbot 003, and activate his effect to Special Summon a Monster, but don't use his second effect. Special Summon Deskbot 002, and activate its effect. Add either Deskbot 005/006 to the hand (Depends on which one you got in the starting hand. If you got 005, add 006 and vice versa). Use Machine Duplication on Deskbot 002, Special Summon the two others in your deck, activate their effects. When it asks you what to add to the hand, add Deskbot Base and Deskbot 007/008 to your hand. Put 005 and 006 into the Spell/Trap Card Zones, Special Summon Deskbot 009. Place down the Bottomless Trap Hole/Twin Twisters. Activate Desktop Base, and if you want, exchange some cards. If you have yet to do so, activate Deskbot 003's effect. Use it on Deskbot 009, and once you do, activate 009's effect (Be amazed!). End your turn, and try to keep Deskbot 003 alive. This is just an example of a combo that you can use, but find more yourself.  

Weaknesses

  A few major weaknesses this deck has are: Mirror Force (Any kind), Effect Negating Cards, Solemn Cards, getting a bad hand, and misclicks.  

Thank you to anyone that looks at this. Enjoy the deck!

deck_excerpt: This is a pretty standard Dark Magician deck with the card Switcheroroo tech'd in.
deck_description: This is a pretty standard Dark Magician deck with the card Switcheroroo tech'd in. This card can singly handedly cripple your opponents combo if used correctly. Open a bad hand? Play 1 monster and set Switcheroroo and then use it to swap with the first monster your opponent summons. It can also be used to swap a Dark Magician for a card that has more ATK power (I love to use it on stuff like Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon), to then attack into the Dark Magician only to have it special summoned back to your side of the field using something like Eternal Soul. The deck also contains 3 copies of Spellbook of Knowledge and 2 copies of Spellbook Magician of Prophecy for a small draw engine. Also contains 2 copies of Scapegoat for two purposes. The first is that on the very rare occasion you may be able to chain it if your opponent has 4 monsters on the field and then chain Switcheroroo too it, giving you 4 of your opponents monsters and giving them 4 Sheep Token. The other is to use it for Link summoning. Chain Scapegoat at the end phase of your opponents turn and you can then summon 2 Missus Radiant from the Sheep Tokens and then further Link Summon into Firewall Dragon or Topologic Bomber Dragon. deck_excerpt: Trickstars combined with the Star Seraph engine. Link Format
deck_description: This deck uses Trickstar, but also takes advantage of the Star-Seraph engine. You have two options you can usually do. You can either use the Star Seraph or the Trickstars. For the Trickstars the usually combos ALWAYS Candina or Lightstage. Depending on your hand of course, I would get lightstage on the board then search Candina or Lycorissia (depending on your hand) and use Candina to search Lycorissica or Trickstar Reincarnation. From there search out Candina for Lycorissica and activate Reincarnation to get big damage. There's multiple ways to pull this off, but the main goal is to bring out holly angel or decode talker to take out your opponent. Don't force the link summon though you have XYZ and synchro for a reason. Star Seraph engine explains itself, summon all 3 to get sentry on the field to take out 1 pesky card. The synchros are meant for Lycorissica and Gofu. I would always resort to Beelze as it is easy to summon and hard to get off the field for some unprepared decks. Double summon is meant to help combos, dark hole, and raigeki for protection. The Solemn cards and Ash Blossom will help stop your oppoenent from advancing their board. Overall, more Trickstars is needed for the TCG and until then combining types is the best method.

Eve the Shrine Maiden is a link card not meant for the extra monster zone. She can protect everything she points to from card effects and she can't be destroy by battle or card effect so she is very handy. I would focus on getting on Borreload or Aurum immediately. Use each spell card wisely and experiment to find out their purpose they can be used multiple ways. The World Legacy and Guarddragon are meant for the graveyard to recycle cards back on the field or to the field. So use them for link summoning. Use Imduk ability in the grave to get World Legacy on the field.  Only 3 traps which help recycle or special summon. Solemn Strike because you can't go wrong with that card. This deck is a good intro into Link summoning in general and if the cards are played right this can take out meta decks.

deck_excerpt: A deck recently featured on Farfa's youtube channel with a few variations.
deck_description: This deck is designed to pump out links and synchros with the primary play makers being Iron Chain Repairman and Iron Chain Coil. Since Repairman isn't a hard once per turn, you can keep reviving him or bring out more of them from the deck to abuse his effect to revive an Iron Chain monster from the graveyard. This deck is extremely consistent as all you need is two level three monsters and a way to send Coil to the graveyard. This can be easily accomplished with cards like Junk Forward, Kagemucha Knight and Marauding Captain giving you free level three monsters and cards like Foolish Burial, Mathematician and Scrap Recycler to send Coil to the graveyard.   Video on a very similar deck from Farfa's channel: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8ii07SXyJck

deck_excerpt: Pendulum Magicians - Consistent and Powerful.
deck_description:
Monsters:

Astrograph Sorcerer: Astrograph Sorcerer is used to + after you use Wavering Eyes, simply activate wavering eyes, search Astrograph Sorcerer, then activate Astrograph Sorcerer's effect and get a free card (Can also be used if you need the scale but I don't recommend unless it's your only play).   Oafdragon Magician: Oafdragon Magician allows you to get a free card back, often Harmonizing Magician but also useful to bring back a scale.   Performpal Skullcrobat Joker: Performpal Skullcrobat Joker gives you a free search, a good strategy is to search Harmonizing Magician and then Pendulum Summoning it out. Black Fang Magician: Black Fang Magician is a floater and a High Scale, you can Special Summon him from the deck using Harmonizing Magician's effect and use him as XYZ material (I recommend another Dark Spellcaster, this allows you to special summon him from another Black Fang Magician's effect and then use his effect to Special Summon the other Dark Spellcaster you used, this grants some decent stall if needed or just more material after you pop it with Time Pendulumgraph), this stops him from being banished and provides free material for his effect. White Wing Magician: White Wing Magician is used as a Low Scale when you have no other options (Or just when you're against a match-up that might target a Dark Spellcaster you control), she is also used as a tuner to go into double Psy-Framelord Omega. Wisdom-Eye Magician: Wisdom-Eye Magician provides a free Scale and he can be Pendulum Summoned afterwards as extra material. Double Iris Magician: Double Iris Magician is your go to High Scale and great for searching out your Pendulumgraph's. Performpal Pendulum Sorcerer: Performpal Pendulum Sorcerer allows you to not only destroy your scales but search Performpal Skullcrobat Joker for another search (Keep in mind that you can destroy both of your Scales to Search Performpal Skullcrobat Joker and your second copy of Performpal Pendulum Sorcerer). Purple Poison Magician: Purple Poison Magician is your general go to Low Scale, he provides removal when he is destroyed and can boost your Dark Spellcaster's attack to Beat over things. Harmonizing Magician: Harmonizing Magician provides you with a free XYZ or Synchro Summon. Ash Blossom and Joyous Spring, Ghost Ogre and Snow Rabbit & Maxx "C": These are your Hand Traps; Destruction, Negates and Draw Power, very useful cards for stopping your Opponent.

Spells:

Pot of Desires: Pot of Desires is used to boost your consistency and give you some Card Advantage. Duelist Alliance: Duelist Alliance allows you to search Double Iris Magician, Performpal Pendulum Sorcerer, Space Pendulumgraph or Time Pendulumgraph. Cosmic Cyclone: Cosmic Cyclone is great S/T Removal. Wavering Eyes: Wavering Eyes is used to Destroy your Scales, Search your Astrograph Sorcerer and if your Opponent is playing Pendulums you can Banish a card they Control then Search another Wavering Eyes. Space Pendulumgraph: Space Pendulumgraph provides you with a free Search when one of your Magician Pendulum Monster's leaves the Field (Usually by Battle, Scale Destruction Effects or when you Synchro Summon).

Traps:

Time Pendulumgraph: Time Pendulumgraph provides you with Protection again threats, it can also be used with Timestar Magician to stop the Destruction of the card you Target giving you both the Destruction and Send Effect.   Extra Deck: Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend: Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend gives you a potential Board Clear and Burn, he's also a Beater which is nice. Ignister Pominence, the Blasting Dracoslayer: Ignister Prominence, the Blasting Dracoslayer provides you the ability to Destroy one of your Pendulum Monsters and then Shuffle one of your Opponent's cards into the Deck. Psy-Framelord Omega: Psy-Framelord Omega is one of your go to Extra Deck Monsters, he can Banish himself to take away one of your Opponent's Cards in their Hand and bring himself back next turn in the Main Monster Zone. Supreme King Dragon Clear Wing: Supreme King Dragon Clear Wing provides a potential Board Clear and Once Per Turn he has the ability to Destroy a Monster he Battles and Inflict Damage to your Opponent equal to the Destroyed Monster's Attack. Enlightenment Paladin: Enlightenment Paladin gives you a free Spell Card and some potential Burn Damage. Supreme King Dragon Dark Rebellion: Supreme King Dragon Dark Rebellion is a huge Beater, Once Per Turn when he Battles and Opponent's Monster he can reduce the Monster's Attack to 0 and gain it until the End Of The Turn (This equates to Damage to your Opponent equal to 2500 + the Opponent's Monster's Attack). Performage Trapeze Magician: Performage Trapeze Magician is an OTK enabler. Timestar Magician: Timestar Magician gives you Search and stops the Destruction of a Pendulum Monster. Tornado Dragon: Tornado Dragon is great on demand S/T Removal. Number 41: Bagooska The Terribly Tired Tapir: Number 41: Bagooska The Terribly Tired Tapir is a Stall card and one of your go to Extra Deck Monsters. Castel, the Skyblaster Musketeer: Castel, the Skyblaster Musketeer is some great on demand Removal. Abyss Dweller: Abyss Dweller stops your Opponent's Graveyard Effects from Activating. Decode Talker: Decode Talker enables you to pump out more Extra Deck Monsters, Pendulum Monsters and Beat over one of your Opponent's Monsters.   Side Deck and Tips coming sometime soon.

-Livid

deck_excerpt: This deck has link combos AND Xyz combos in the OCG, but over here we've gotta rely on more archaic methods of OTKing the opponent. You end up sitting
deck_description: Essentially you want to make big plays with the unholy insect trinity of Inzektor Dragonfly, Inzektor Hornet, and Inzektor Giga-Mantis. Because two of these three play makers are at one, however, we have to get creative in alternative plays and consistency that doesn't harm this very specific combo deck. The Summoner Monk 'engine' provides a consistency boost in discarding dead spells (including Metalfoes Fusion, a spell that let's you draw 1 by shuffling it from the grave into the deck) to summon Armageddon Knight, which can dump a Farfa for some light removal or an Inzektor piece, or maybe a hopper to facilitate hornet, then make a rank 4 play. Overall a super fun strategy that will (hopefully) get a significant boost with its new link monster.

deck_excerpt: A mix between Constellars and other powerful Monsters like "The Supremacy Sun"," Vanity Ruler"," Guardian Of Order".
deck_description: Well, the easiest way to explain it is that you keep XYZ summon Monsters Using Constellars Monsters which are amazing for that because They can give you Rank 4,5,6 XYZ Constellars very fast. Also, You can easily keep your hand full of Constellars monsters. I Guess you could also Benefits from all Constellars XYZ Effects, Which Are:  Constellar Omega (Rank 4): Your Constellar Monsters aren't affected by your opponent spell or trap card till the end of either players turn.     Constellar Praesepe (Rank 4): One Constellar monster gains 1000 Attack points, During either player turn, Till the end of that turn.     Constellar Pleiades (Rank 5): Return one card on the field to its controller hand, during either player turn.     Constellar Ptolemy M7 (Rank 6): You can XYZ this Monsters by using any XYZ  Constellar Monster you control as the XYZ material. Only during your turn, You can return one monster card from either player field or graveyard to its Owner Hand.-----------------------------------------------------------------     You may be asking "What the hell is umbral have to do in this deck?!" Well, the answer is a simple Trap Card Called "Corrupted Keys" Which Allow you To target An XYZ monster you control and summon Three Umbral Tokens (ATK:??,DEF:00) its attack is the attack of your XYZ Monster. They can't attack your opponent directly.     You can use them to clean your opponent field of Monsters then attack directly with you XYZ Monster. Or you can easily tribute them to summon a high level Monster (Like An Egyptian God monster for example).     This deck also has A variety of spell cards especially for this archetype.     So, I was very, very surprised (and Angry) to notice that no one seems to use this amazing Archetype. With a little tweak here and there I made this deck very powerful.     If anyone have anything to say (Good or bad) about this deck, please write. It will only help me make it much better.

deck_excerpt: Blue-eyes classic deck
There hasn't been going on much going on with true king dino after deng long and lithosagym was banned... here in this deck I collected some of the tr
deck_description:
The deck currently presented here with out the side is true king dino kaiju, where the sea turtle grants easier summon with bahrasto (same with dogoran and Agnimazud) and kaiju grant more destructive power blablabla for details go look at the recent article about true king dino (good article). The most interesting thing i implemented in the deck is that kaiju and jurrac dino give access to star eater, and tyranno and aeolo does the same thing. kaiju and aeolo could also gain access to Chaofeng, Legend of the Yang Zing which could replace dragon of the ice barrier. Although we have to agree that dragon of the ice barrier is strong but the fact that it needs 3 or more monsters to summon makes it hard bring out on to the field. true kings and aeolo give access to Leo the gate keeper. For more resistance, drop a few PSY or ash blossoms and ghost orge into the deck, replace the kaijus with them. Yazi yang zing and mare mare could be added into the deck.  The down side of this combo is that mare mare is a water wyrm monster and could not be summoned by Bahrastos (but it helps with the summoning of Bahratos). true draco phoenix Marriamne and black ptera could also be added into the deck, but i suggest not because it is hard to summon. Although tornado dragon and Castel was added help with it, but again, it works better with Yangzing dino because there is Pulao, wind of the Yang Zing.Although deng long was a body blow to yang zing dino, it is still playable. If you want look at a true king yang zing dino deck, go check out snavar98's deck. Elemental Lord Pyrorex could also be dropped in, but i suggest against it since it could not be summoned by the pill and has a very limited summoning condition. Tyranno infinity could dropped in to cover some attack weaknesses. the effect of lost world and its uses go find in the article, they do a better job of explaining it. The above are my suggestions for true king dino arch type, hope you find it helpful. Changes to the deck:
  1. Chaofeng, Legend of the Yang Zing has been added of its easy summon condition and that the fact it grants easier passway to sychro. There is also the fact it could possibly summon mare mare or the other true kings.
  2. Yazi, Evil of the Yang Zing and mare mare has been added. I have realised, after reminders of others, that Yazi itself fits in a more aggro play style, whereas the ancient fairy dragon that have been replaced fits with a combo play style. Whereas ancient fairy dragon could be useful, i believe that Yazi itself is a much more useful monster in terms of its effect and the fact that it could bring mare mare to the board, opening more room for synchro.
  3. The seven sins has been added as i realised one of the weaknesses of the deck. Sometimes when we have the ultimate conductor and the True King of All Calamities on the board there is simply not enough resistance. Also the two monster have a very similar effect in terms of controlling the opponent's monsters. There are specific situations where Number 77 would prove as much better choice.
  4. I have come to realise that there is no possible way to summon overtex coatls because the pill does not work on him and the fact that there could be no possible 5 banished dinosaurs. however, Overtex Coatls could be considered being put into the deck along with Soul Release and Tyranno Infinity.
  5. Soul Charge was added into the deck. Although true king dino has an incredible ability of building up a strong board, its power to build up a new board after the old one was destroyed proved weak. So therefore soul could very much help you in mid or late game.
  6. One of the two  Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju has been taken away because of adding of mare mare.
Update for V0.3 link format update (as i have recently just studied link format)
  1. Crystron Needlefiber is added for new path to synchro, Celestial Double Star Shaman is added for Crystron's effect, as there are probably a few Babycerasauras and Petiteranodon in your hand or graveyard. Number 77 is removed to make room for the link monsters. Also, as Crystron is water, it also applies to Bahrastos' effect
  2. Chaofeng has been removed as i realised we could come with few situations of being able summon the monster. Whereas PSY Framelord, can be easily summoned by Celestial or Jurrac Dino +Hi-Speedroid Chanbara.
  3. Castel has been removed as it is one of the least frequent played monster while encountering different situations.
  4. Firewall Dragon has been added because of its easy to summon conditions and its second effect.
Please give more suggestions on improving the deck.

deck_excerpt: A mostly standard Krawler deck that eschews expensive Hand Traps in favour of cheaper options for accessible IRL play.
deck_description:
The basic strategy of a Krawler deck involves playing defensively while slowly but surely building up resources. Their FLIP effects disrupt your opponent, gather or recover cards, and help swarm, and if your opponent decides to negate one, they'll probably do so with a card that also destroys, triggering their powerful effects to swarm further directly from the deck. As you build up resources, you can spend them on their Link Monsters, which turn these innocent insects into powerful attackers with stacking buff effects, and if your opponent does deal with them, you get the resources you spent to make them back. Some specific techs of note in detail:
  • Block Spider can be Special Summoned by the effect of World Legacy in Shadow, triggering its effect for a cheap Link or an attack lock.
  • Scapegoat, besides just being general Link assistance, is usfeul for a specific combo: use one Sheep Token to create Link Spider in the Extra Monster Zone, then two more tokens for X-Krawler Synaphysis beneath it, then the Spider and your last token for a second Synaphysis next to it. Their effects affect each other, and the Extra Monster Zone is free to put something else with down-facing arrows in there.
  • It's worth noting that besides other Krawlers, Verdant Sanctuary can also search Maxx "C".
  • Lose 1 Turn may seem out of place, but with how slow-paced the deck is, Link Monsters remaining in ATK position, and a lot of action happening on your opponent's turn, it hinders you little enough to be worth using it against a Special Summon heavy opponent.
As Side Decks are largely dependent on what you expect to face, I've opted to use it to illustrate other options instead. Besides extra Krawlers for tweaking ratios to taste, and Book of Eclipse - which can blow out certain match-ups but is near-worthless against Link-heavy decks - it contains some spicy techs.
  • Karakuri Strategist mdl 248 "Nishipachi" is a Level 3 Tuner that can get you to Naturia Beast with only 1 Krawler non-Tuner, as well as flipping a face-down Krawler to apply its effect. However, the deck can't afford any more Normal Summons.
  • Junk Synchron can revive a Krawler to make Junk Warrior, which can gain ATK from any Krawlers you control. This is nothing more than a meme.
  • Speaking of memes, Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier can theoretically be summoned with 3-4 Krawlers and any of the deck's odd-leveled Tuners.
  • Inzektor Picofarena can help recover resources, as well as an interesting interaction with the Krawlers' floating - it works from the Spell/Trap zone. In addition, you can play actual Inzektors for their effects, and they can be summoned from the deck by tributing a Krawler with Insect Imitation.

deck_excerpt: What happened to Atlantean Mermail after the link transformation? What tech choices could be implemented?
deck_description:
Experienced players should have a descent understanding of how to play the mermail archtype. And I am here, not to rephrase the combos, but to explain why this mermail deck is different from the others.
  1. Specified spell and trap cards that support different situations: Eisbahn, Aquamirror Cycle, Big wave small wave, and sea lord's amulet. they are put into the side deck because they are useless in most situations but can be real useful in a match.
  2. The drop in of Galaxy Tomahawk. This enables access borreload dragon or Skulldeat the chained dracoserpent.
  3. The drop in of number 47. First of all because it is able to be summoned by bahumut and able to attach xyz materials. Second of all, mermail abssdine grants access to number 47. Third of all, number 47 and Abyssmegalo could bite huge chunk of blood off the opponent without monsters standing in between.
  4. Mermail Abyssmander and Abyssturge grants more access to the bahumut shark, at the same time Abyssmander grants access to the True King of All Calamities.
  5. Elemental lord is added in because it could be easily searched by Atlantean Dragoons.
  6. the sea turtle kaiju added for destruction of the board
  7. Surface added for consistency into later games.
  8. Typical deep sea diva synchro pathway kept.
  9. Mask change 2 and Masked Hero Acid could be added against opponents like paleozoic frogs
  10. Abyss-Squall could be added for consistency and late game.
Play this deck, enjoy, and give suggestions in the comments section below.

deck_description:
This deck is not for link (for those who play pendulum era only) if you have any questions about this deck you can contact me on discord: StealthAngel#2555   Older versions of this deck: 30 march: http://www.mediafire.com/file/9a566itxr09acjj/16101.ydk 2 oct 2020: https://www.mediafire.com/file/ufjq3eb36roo152/16101%25282%2529.ydk way before: http://www.mediafire.com/file/6bjnee1bsih76nb/A%20Brokenfoes%20v0.46%20%28Mo_D_Genesis%29.ydk

Summary

This deck depends on your metalfoes skill. If you can play metalfoes this deck will work greatly in your favor. I won't be covering the metalfoes basics since there is enough information on the internet out there. I might make a video in the future on how to make plays with this deck. It will be posted here. You can learn to play metalfoes by practicing. A good beginner idea is to destroy all your metalfoe cards and end up with a pendulum scale 1 - 8 so you can summon your monsters back.

Why do we run 46 cards as opposed to 40 cards?

This deck has good drawing power. If you are going to utilize your side deck, you can still utilize your main cards without needing to sacrifice good cards you need. Wind bitches = 6. Assuming that you get your wind witch combo right ur left with 43 cards in your deck. If you remove wind witches you have 41 cards. Whats wrong with 41 cards :)  

strengths

  • High piercing damage on defence monsters
  • great summoning power
  • great recovery
  • Great Defence ability.
  • ability to steal opponents monsters
  • nice field of monsters and facedown cards
  • draw power
  • awesome side deck
  • glorious extra deck if used well

weaknesses

  • solemn strike (don't over summon if you think your opponent has it don't summon all your monsters have some just in case)
  • evenly matched (wtf is this card)
  • relies on special summoning
  • with endless nightmare you are fucked unless you can do something about it
  • you will have issues with untargetable monsters or monsters such as Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon (the solution for this is number s39 or you use metalfoes orichalc and metalfoes mithrilium)
  • weak if your card are getting banished
  • not the best backrow destroyer such as spells and traps (you might place some twin twisters in this deck if that is a problem)

Monsters

Metalfoes Mithrilium

If this card is used right it is one of the best cards. You can shuffle your opponent cards to their hand but also your own cards. kaijus can be brought back to your hand. The best idea with mithrilium is sending one of your own metalfoes monster on the field to your hand so that you have the missing pendulum scale in for summoning pendulums. Shuffle nopes to your opponents hand. Shuffle cards you need back to your own hand. Also if this card is destroyed you can recover 1 metalfoe normal monster from your graveyard or pendulum zone. Overal great defence.

Metalfoes orichalc

If you need to quickly destroy a card on the field, you can destroy with your pendulum zone this card to destroy one card on the field. Also this baby is your main piercing damage amplifier. Also with metalfoes combination you can fusion summon mithrilium with a pendulum monster for orichalc and they will all come back on the field.

Metalfoes alkahest

Steal his monster if needed.

Kaijus (tributing their monsters optional)

You have a choice between:
  • Lava Golem
  • The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode
  • Kumongous, the Sticky String Kaiju
Those three are your main to go kaijus for this deck. The reason kaijus work with this deck is that you can bring them back to your hand with Metalfoes Mithrilium. Sphere also works but it requires 3 tributes although sphere can be a game changing moment, lava golem will almost certainly guarantee that you remove 2 monsters on the field. Use whatever of those 3 monsters you like. Two kaijus in your deck is more than enough. The usefull thing about Kumongous, the Sticky String Kaiju is that you can pendulum summon it, and tributing your opponents monster requires no normal summon.

Rescue Rabbit

you get to summon 2 metalfoes. This card is a must have in this deck.

Astrograph Sorcerer

Some people prefer using  Majespecter Raccoon - Bunbuku But astrograph gives you more utility. If a card is destroyed you can summon it and you can bring one metalfoe monster from your deck to your hand. It also helps you with summoning number Number 11: Big Eye This card also has a pendulum scale 1 so it balances it out with Raremetalfoes Bismugear

Archfiend Eccentrick

This card is great because it can destroy a spell card or a monster card. Some people prefer having 3 of them in your deck. However, having 3 of those cards in your extra deck is meaningless since you will be summoning metalfoes most of the times. 2 of them is more than enough. Also you can use archfiend eccentrick on Metalfoes Combination  to get another metalfoe in your hand.

Luster Pendulum, the Dracoslayer

This card is next level with metalfoes. with 1 metalfoe monster and luster pendulum you can get another metalfoe to your hand.

Wind bitches

Free Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon? And with pendulum summon you can get a clear wing fast dragon as bonus? Get your hands on it. If you, however don't like them, you can remove them from the deck. If your opponent gives you a hard time doing the wind witch combo, then u can always replace them with your side deck cards. The wind witches are inside to give you more options. The only downside is that you can only summon wind monsters the turn you activate it. Play wisely. On a side note: with Windwitch - Glass Bell and a metalfoe monster you can summon clear wing fast dragon. If you also have Windwitch - Snow Bell then u can get Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon regardless.

Spells

Swords of Concealing Light (optional as opposed to quacking mirror force)

The reason for this card as opposed to a mirror force is that you can get this card back in your hand with Metalfoes Mithrilium

Also they are on defence position on your turn so with metalfoes orichalc you can get dem piercing damage on their faces :)

Supply Squad

since metalfoes are basically destroying their own monsters with card effects, supply squad works for having great draw power. 2 is enough because you don't want 3 of those in your hands or on the field.

Painful Decision

This is your card for getting a metalfoe from your deck. Since you can only use 1 per turn I won't recommend 2 of those in your deck.   Plays

deck_excerpt: True Draco Engine + Synchros (weaker search engine, burns fast, strong beatdown potential, extra-deck spam capacity is there)
deck_description:
Strategy:

  • Objective: Summon Metaltron XII, the True Dracombatant by means of 3 tributes
    • Let opponent trigger Metaltron eff. or keep the 3000/3000 beater (if you have dragonic --> 3.3k/3.3k beater)
This deck relies on the True Draco engine, though it can not pull of the card advantage that was once typical of True Draco. The engine is not used in this deck to establish card advantage, though it can be useful for this purpose, but to bring out Metaltron. Metaltron can be brought out in 2 ways.
  • 1.) Tribute Summon - requires 3 (3 spells, 0 monsters | 2 spells, 1 monster | 1 spell, 2 monsters | 0 spells, 3 monsters)
    • This is ideal as it allows you to trigger Metaltron's eff - which can be used to delve into the synchro portion of the extra deck as needed
  • 2.) Dreiath III, the True Dracocavalry General: this card's eff is upon being sent to the graveyard (you can tribute this card for another True Draco or for metaltron itself - and bring out another metaltron, etc.) it allows you to summon any True Draco monster - which includes Metaltron (though this negates the eff of Metaltron and should only be used if you need a defensive card or a beater).
Aside from bringing out Metaltron, details above, the deck focuses on gradual spell advantage through the True Draco spell system - which can not be searched due to the limitation of Ignis and ban of Dinomight Knight. The spell system works in that traps are used to destroy opponent's monsters - and bring out True Draco monsters - and spells are used in one of two ways. True Draco Heritage allows you to draw and is the most basic card when it comes to spell advantage, it should always be set before a spell/trap tribute summon of a true draco spell/trap --> gives you a +1 card advantage. The second spell is Disciples of the True Dracopheonix which can serve as fodder in the beginning of a duel but must be kept around for later in a duel so that the True Draco engine can be kept alive; as this card allows you to recycle cards such as Dreiath and Metaltron - which are key to bringing out Metaltron and the Sycnhros associated with his eff. Other Important Cards:
  • Masterpeace: Same use as in previous True Draco decks, though this is not necessarily the boss "monster" of the deck anymore. Masterpeace serves as a card that can shut down and/or prevent chains - as well as give you ridiculous card advantage. I keep 2 but if you prefer Master Peace to Metaltron, use  3.
  • Ash Blossom...: Standard hand trap, multi-purpose and won't trigger graveyard effs (though you can replace Ash with Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit if you'd prefer sending to graveyard)
  • Dragonic Diagram: Allows you to search for true draco spells/traps/monsters --> Key to speeding up the engine and securing Metaltron through 3 tributes. Not the most important card in the deck but it acts as the primary searcher, allowing you to trigger spell/trap effects and bring more into your hand.
    • Ideal combos: Dragonic Diagram (activation) --> tribute of fodder card (useless card) or Dreiath --> Summon Metaltron or Ignis from Dreiath eff --> obtain something like True Draco Heritage or Dracopheonix from sacrifice (whatever is more appropriate for the situation) --> Use to gain card advantage --> beatdown + spell/trap destruction --> repeat
  • Extra Deck Synchros: Many are situational but some can be used in any battle as a boss monster that can guarantee victory. Personally I'd bring out Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon for it's effect but Barbaroid has one of the most brutal effects available to you and can help beef up a deck that is otherwise lacking in immediate offensive firepower.
Not really sure what else to say here, so I'll leave it at that. If you have any tips, I guess you can contact me on here?

deck_excerpt: Rokkets are the cybernetic dragons used by Yu-Gi-Oh! VRAINS's Revolver to power his signature monster, the Link-4 behemoth, Borreload Dragon.
deck_description: The main strategy here is to Link Summon as soon as possible to get out your roadblocker, Linkbelt Wall Dragon This guy makes it so your opponent has to get a strong enough Link monster out on the field, but, with the added effect that you can only Link Summon up to the amount of Counters on Linkbelt, if you can manage to get the counters to 0, no Link Summoning, now this is a double-edged sword, so be careful not to impale yourself on it The Rokkets' main purpose, in this deck, are to get in your opponent's way, Anesthrokket Dragon is the card you'll want the most with it's DEF of 2200, boostable to 2500 with their Field Spell, Revolve Boot Sector, which has a sort of reverse-Evenly Matched effect, if your opponent controls more monsters than you, you can summon Rokkets from your GY in Defense Position up to the surplus You can also, during your turn, Special Summon up to 2 Rokket monsters from hand in Defense Position, if you already have monster's on the field, this more often than let's you go straight into Borreload, which sets up a whole load of different combos with the Rokkets, they all have different effects which let you take care of cards your opponent has that's annoying you, Shelrokket Dragon let's you also destroy monsters in adjacent zones This deck can already do a hell of a lot, and until it becomes Meta-Relavant, it's just going to keep getting better and better with every new card that comes out for them.

deck_excerpt: A deck I created after researching Xyz's and the anime Yu-Gi-Oh Zexal series. It's inspired by the Chaos Xyzs, Utopias and 100+ Numbers that were feat
deck_description: This is a zexal-inspired deck that works around summoning Xyz's (non-link format, so you can't spam anymore) with the purpose of bringing out their CXyz (Chaos Xyz form). As it's namesake might suggest, the boss monster - and goal - is to bring about CXyz Barian Hope. The best way to bring about Barian Hope would be to use C101: Silent Honor Dark - which has an effect that allows you to pile on more Overlay material for Barian Hope, which boosts Hope's ATK/DEF. This can lead to an OTK, as it's not difficult to reach a 5000/5000 or 6000/6000 beater with CXyz Barian Hope. Aside from the boss monster, the deck revolves around the Utopia Chaos series - enabling you to deal damage or prevent damage, depending on the situation; and given other situations, there are various Xyzs - Castel (clearing), Honor Ark (card destruction + clearing), etc.  Basics: Most of the spells exist, in the counts that they are in, to speed up the summoning of a Chaos Xyz - but there are some reinforcement cards in spells like Xyz Territory and Xyz Tribal Rivals (the latter of which can make a nearly indestructible board). The Monsters exist, too, in their current number for the purpose of summoning an Xyz in a turn or two.

deck_excerpt: All about hand traps.dek
deck_description: This deck showcases a control strategy, with the PSY-Framegears disrupting the opponent's actions heavily, PSY-Frame Overload banishing the opponent's cards and the PSY-Frame Synchro monsters disrupting the opponent's hand and field actions.  Foolish Burial Goods is there to send Overload to the Graveyard, turning it into an easy search on the next turn. Artifact Lancea was my tech choice as it protects your Gears and Drivers if you do not control Circuit or have a free monster zone for your Synchro Summons. Beatrice and Big Eye were chose over other Xyz because of their great synergy with PSY-Frames, Beatrice for enabling Multi-Threader and Overload plays and Big Eye for stealing the opposing monsters as a last resort. Overall, this is a good rogue deck, capable of facing most strategies and unleashing very powerful options, such as PSY-Framelord Omega and Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon to opress the opponent.

Also Gozen Match is extremely powerful vs. decks that utilize more than 1 attribute. Scapegoat is your gateway to access Link Summons, while the Solemn Traps, Skill Drain and Macro Cosmos provide disruption and powerful floodgates. Metaverse ensures that you maintain your field spells active and also serves to disrupt Graveyard-reliant decks by activating Necrovalley directly from the Deck.

deck_name: Legacy of the Thousand Eyed One
deck_excerpt: A deck containing the new Relinquished and Eyes Restrict legacy support. Can be played differently depending on if user goes first or second.
deck_description:
Legacy of the Thousand Eyed One

As you can probably already see, this deck is filled with the new legacy support for Relinquished and Eyes Restrict monsters. Why? Because they're amazing! Millenium-Eyes Restrict is capable of countering some of the most annoying Effect Monsters. It's effect reads: "Once per turn, when an opponent's monster activates its effect (Quick Effect): You can target 1 Effect Monster your opponent controls or in their GY; equip that target to this card. Gains ATK/DEF equal to the combined ATK/DEF of the monsters equipped to it by this effect. Monsters with the same name as a monster equipped to this card by this card's effect cannot attack, also negate their effects." Millenium-Eyes Restrict is capable of equipping more than one monster at a time, a feat that used to be impossible. Plus, it if the opponent activates an effect, just equip it to yourself. Problem solved! Millenium-Eyes Illusionist is another great example of amazing support. It's effect reads:  "(Quick Effect): You can discard this card, then target 1 Effect Monster your opponent controls; equip that target to 1 "Eyes Restrict" Fusion Monster or "Relinquished" you control, and if you do, it is treated as being equipped by the equipped monster's effect. If an "Eyes Restrict" Fusion Monster or "Relinquished" is Special Summoned: Add this card from your GY to your hand. You can only use each effect of "Millennium-Eyes Illusionist" once per turn." This card can be used for Ritual Summoning Relinquished with ease because when Relinquished is Special Summoned, M-E Illusionist is returned from the GY to your hand. It also can be used similarly to a handtrap as it's first effect can counter cards.

Magical Illusionist Faceless Mage is perfect candidate for post-Instant Fusion. "If a face-up "Eyes Restrict" Fusion Monster or "Relinquished" you control is destroyed by battle or card effect while this card is in your hand or GY: You can Special Summon this card. If this card is sent from the field to the GY: You can target 1 "Eyes Restrict" Fusion Monster or "Relinquished" in your GY; Special Summon it. You can only use each effect of "Magical Illusionist Faceless Mage" once per turn." Basically, Instant Fusion an Eyes Restrict while MIFM is in hand, end turn once satisfied, kill the IF target, Special Summon MIFM. You got a body right there! You can also send it from the field to the GY to Special Summon that IF target back to the field. Rinse, repeat, victory!

Relinquished Fusion the Quick-Play Fusion Card for the "archetype." Fusion Summon 1 "Eyes Restrict" Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck, by banishing Fusion Materials from your hand, field, and/or GY. During your Main Phase: You can banish this card from your GY, then target 1 Effect Monster your opponent controls; equip that target to 1 "Eyes Restrict" Fusion Monster or "Relinquished" you control, and if you do, it is treated as being equipped by the equipped monster's effect. You can only use each effect of "Relinquished Fusion" once per turn. Yet another way to use Equip shenanigans. Those are the major cards to worry about. Have fun with the deck! :D

deck_excerpt: This deck is a pretty simple take on the Windwitch Speedroid strategy. It plays pretty straightforward, with your main goal being to summon Clear Wing
deck_description: This deck is a pretty simple take on the Windwitch Speedroid strategy. It plays pretty straightforward, with your main goal being Clear Wing Fast Dragon and the indestructible Crystal Wing, and there are plenty of combos you can pull off. One thing you may notice is that I decided to run three of every Windwitch. Although most strategies only run 3 Ice Bell, 2 Glass Bell, and 1 Snow Bell, I decided to run 3 of all 3. This is because you will always have two Wind-type monsters on the field when synchro summoning, so filling Snow Bell's condition is easy and makes for even easier indestructible Crystal Wing summons. I kept Ice Bell at 3 for obvious reasons, due to it being the catalyst for the instant indestructible Crystal Wing. One thing I was debating was whether or not to leave Glass Bell at two, but I eventually decided to put it at three due to it also being able to create the indestructible Crystal Wing when paired with Taketomborg due to it being Normal Summoned, searching out Snow Bell, then Special Summoning Taketomborg from hand, then using Snow Bell's effect to Special Summon it, and then go into the indestructible Crystal Wing. Plus, it is a searcher for any Windwitch, which can help improve consistency.

deck_excerpt: Try this out!
deck_description: Your goal is to summon King of the skull servant. First of all, it's highly recommended to send as many skull servants as possibile to the graveyard, in order to increase King's attack. Your first strategy consists into sending wightprice from your hand/deck to the graveyard: use Gozuki's effect or card trooper's effect. In this way, you'll be able to activate wightprince's effect, and send a skull servant and a lady in wight from the deck/hand to the graveyard. The cheerful coffin is another useful card because allows you to send monster from you hand to the graveyard.  Once wightprince, skull servant and the lady in wight have been sent to the graveyard, you can activate wightprince's effect: banish all these 3 monsters and special summon the king from your deck. Now you can activate burial from another dimension to bring back your 3 monsters and boost the king's attack.  Wall of light and gravity bind are useful cards to control the field and to give you the time to set your board with 1/2 kings with 3k/4k atk points each. Extra deck is not necessary, but this deck can easily spam monsters even thanks to zombie master, and borreload dragon is quite strong.

deck_excerpt: Pendulum Magician FTK Turbo (With Tutorial)
deck_description:
After seeing the Pendulum Magician FTK, I decided to make a build myself and I came up with one that is similar to most people's Pendulum Magician FTK build but some of my card choices are slightly different than everyone elses. This deck is pretty consistent for the FTK and you can expect to FTK your opponent maybe once every match and even if you can't, then just use regular Pendulum Magician combos and set up Odd-Eyes Vortex Dragon! The FTK is not too hard, I will explain the easiest way to do it, right now. First, you need to link summon one Heavymetalfoes Electrum by using Astrograph Sorcerer and/or Cronograph Sorcerer and/or Supreme King Darkwurm to special summon and/or you can normal summon too to get the Electrum. After that you need to get five dark pendulum monsters on the field (six monsters total including the Electrum in the extra monster zone) by pendulum summoning. Then make a second Heavymetalfoes Electrum. Also, you MUST have Instant Fusion in your hand to bring out the FTK fusion target (Lyrilusc - Independent Nightingale).  You can place Supreme King Gate Zero and Supreme King Gate Infinity in your scales and use Gate Zero's effect to search an Instant Fusion if you don't have it in hand already. But don't use the Instant Fusion until the end! Make sure to use both Electrum's effects in the process of summoning them to special summon Astrograph and/or Cronograph and get a free draw.  Next, link those Electrums away to get Zefra Metaltron. Then, contact fuse the four left over dark pendulum monsters to get out two Supreme King Dragon Starving Venoms and use Instant Fusion to get out Lyrilusc.  Finally, copy Lyrilusc's effect using the Supreme King Dragon Starving Venoms and use both Starving Venom's effects to deal burn damage to them worth eight-thousand life points! This is the easiest way to FTK your opponent using this deck, but there are other plays in this deck to get the Instant Fusion to bring out Lyrilusc and use the Supreme King Starving Venoms to burn them for game. If you manage to figure out the other ways you can truly master this deck and FTK your opponent every game if you go first and they don't have any handtraps! I will list the steps below : Steps To FTK Your Opponent Using Dark Pendulum Monsters:
  1. Make sure you have an Instant Fusion in your hand
  2. Link summon 2 Heavymetalfoes Electrums while having 4 dark pendulum monsters on the field via pendulum summon
  3. Use those Electrums to link summon Zefra Metaltron
  4. Contact fuse for 2 Supreme King Starving Venoms
  5. Use the Instant Fusion to bring out Lyrilusc - Independent Nightingale
  6. Copy Lyrilusc's effect using the 2 Supreme King Dragon Starving Venoms
  7. Use both of the Starving Venoms effects to burn your opponent for 8k!
Thanks For Checking Out My Deck Profile And FTK Tutorial! - MindReader

deck_excerpt: Inspired by Dragon Horn Hunter, this deck consists almost entirely of Normal monsters that are supported by powerful Pendulum effects, allowing for a
deck_description:
Main Deck

The majority of monsters in this deck are, for all intents and purposes, the same - Powerful Level 4 monsters with 2000 ATK and 0 - 100 DEF. On their own, they can give you a steady start to a game, providing a solid defensive line. With the assistance of Dragon Horn Hunter, these monsters become just that little bit stronger and also protect you from battle damage entirely. Use cards like Heat Wave or Tyrant's Throes to gain a huge advantage over your opponents (Provided they aren't playing a similar deck) by cutting off their most powerful monsters and allowing you to build up field presence in the meantime, picking off their tributes and other weaker monsters. If Sea Dragoons of Draconia is in the Pendulum zone, attacking your opponent will also enable you to get an extra monster out each turn during the Battle Phase. Depending on the opponent, Tyrant's Throes can almost become a win condition for this deck, stifling your opponent's summoning capacity completely while leaving yours untouched and allowing you to attack directly every turn. Sky Dragoons of Draconia has a powerful Pendulum effect that allows you to double up on monster destruction each time you attack with one of your Normal monsters, useful for disposing of high-ATK targets, or to eliminate threats in your opponent's Spell & Trap card zones. Alternatively, you can use it to clear out a Pendulum zone you no longer need to replace it for a new one. Summoner's Art can be used to search out Dragon Horn Hunter or Sky Dragoons of Draconia to start off your Pendulum setup, or in tandem with Ancient Rules to bring out a Blue Eyes White Dragon or Dragon Core Hexer.

Extra Deck

One of the easiest possible strategies to pull off with this deck is to use Dragon's Mirror and Link Spider to summon First of the Dragons. Summon any Normal monster while you have another Level 4 or lower in hand, then Link summon Link Spider. Use its effect to bring out the second monster, and then use Dragon's Mirror to banish the one in the Graveyard and the one on the field as Fusion materials. Princess Cologne can be used as an easy barricade if you come under pressure from attacks. Combined with Dragon Horn Hunter's Pendulum effect, she can usually buy you at least one turn to recover.

Alterations

  • Dragon Core Hexer is mostly in this deck as a thematic compliment to Dragon Horn Hunter. Mechanically, she isn't much better than Blue Eyes unless you want to use her as a defensive wall. She could easily be traded out for a third Blue Eyes or similar monster.
  • Alternate Pendulum choices may include Lancephorhynchus to give all your Normal monsters piercing damage, or Master Pendulum, The Dracoslayer to help manage your Pendulum zones.

deck_excerpt: A D/D/D Deck (before m4) that retains the OTK potential of traditional D/D/D decks with emphasis on Crystal Wing Turbo; synergizing with Crystal Wing
deck_description:
Rule #1: All "D/D/D" monsters count as "D/D" monsters, but "D/D" monsters do not count as "D/D/D" monsters. So "D/D/D Oracle King D'Arc" is both a D/D/D and D/D monster but "D/D Savant Kepler" is only a "D/D" monster and cannot be considered otherwise. (Likened to Square and Rectangle relationship)
Basic Fusion Combos:
 Swirl Slime + any "D/D" (<-- remember that all D/D/D monsters are also D/D) monster = Fusion Monster (if a fusion monster(s) lists D/D/D --> then you must fuse Swirl with a D/D/D --> if the fusion monster requires 2 D/D/D, then unfortunately you can't use Swirl Slime to bring it out).
Necro Slime combos with cards in the Graveyard to pull off fusion summons. So if you have both Swirl Slime and Necro Slime --> you can activate Swirl Slime =andFusion Summon 1 "D/D/D" monster that does not list "D/D/D" as a fusion requirement; and then you can do it again --> Just activate "Necro Slime" in the Graveyard --> another Fusion Summon of a "D/D/D" monster that does not list "D/D/D" in its summoning requirements.
Goal: Crystal Wing + either D/D/D Cursed King Siegfried or D/D/D High Flame King Genghis (Siegfried is preferable) = Soft lock
Go-To Combo: 
- Hand for Combo: D/D Swirl Slime, D/D Necro Slime, D/D/D King Abyss Ragnarok, D/D Lamia (A Dark Contract with the Gate will help you correct your hand along with draw cards & Kepler <-- a secondary searcher that helps start searching by adding a Dark Contract to your hand).
1. --> You activate Swirl with Necro --> Bring out D/D/D Flame King Genghis 2. --> You Summon D/D Lamia normally, from your hand --> You Synchro Summon D/D/D Gust King Alexander (using D/D Lamia (level 1 tuner) + D/D/D Flame King Genghis (level 6 Fusion)) 3. --> Activate "D/D Swirl Slime" GY effect which allows you to banish D/D Swirl Slime from the GY and Special Summon one card from your hand --> You Special Summon D/D/D Oblivion Abyss King Ragnarok which has the effect that when it is Summoned to the field you can Special Summon 1 "D/D" monster from the GY. 4. --> By Special Summoning "Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok" through "Swirl Slime" <-- you trigger "Gust King Alexander" (which allows you to bring back one "D/D" monster from the Graveyard that is level 4 or less) --> So you bring back "D/D Lamia" 5. --> Now you have a field of "D/D/D Gust King Alexander" + "D/D/D Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok" + "D/D Lami". Ragnarok has its effect triggered by being summoned--> which allows you to bring out "D/D/D Flame King Genghis" from the Graveyard. --> Now you have a board of "D/D/D Gust King Alexander" + "D/D/D Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok" + "D/D/D Flame King Genghis" + "D/D Lamia" ***By Special Summoning "D/D Lamia" you trigger the effect of "Flame King Genghis" (which allows you to special summon 1 D/D monster from the Graveyard) --> BUT, IGNORE THIS FOR NOW *** Keep in mind, your board is now: "D/D Lamia" + "D/D/D Gust King Alexander" + "D/D/D Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok" + "D/D/D Flame King Genghis" 6. --> You Synchro Summon using "D/D Lamia" and "D/D/D Gust King Alexander" for a Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon 7. --> Then, bring back "D/D Lamia" by using it's Graveyard effect (banish the "D/D/D Oblivion King Abyss Ragnarok" from the field as cost) 8. --> Board: "Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon" + "D/D/D Flame King Genghis" + "D/D Lamia" "D/D Lamia" Special Summon triggers the effect of "D/D/D Flame King Genghis", which allows you to Special Summon a D/D monster from your GY; so you bring Back "D/D/D Gust King Alexander" and Synchro Summon "D/D/D Cursed King Siegfried" with the revived "D/D/D Gust King Alexander" + "D/D Lamia". 9. --> Activate "Necro Slime" in your GY; fusion "D/D Necro Slime" + "D/D/D Gust King Alexander" in your GY to bring out "D/D/D Flame High King Genghis" End Board-->  "Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon" + "D/D/D Cursed King Siegfried" + "D/D/D Flame High King Genghis" (Siegfried and Genghis can each negate 1 Spell/Trap per turn and Crystal Wing negates one monster effect; this is one of the best soft locks possible from this deck) --> 1 Monster Eff Negation + 2 Spell/Trap Negation + 8600 ATK

deck_excerpt: The Dark Magician and Buster Blader deck you never knew you needed.
deck_description:
Go first, set up the Destruction Sword lock on your opponent's turn, OTK turn 3. Some notable combos: Combo #1: Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman.
  1. Normal Summon Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman.
  2. Search Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman.
  3. Link Summon Linkuriboh.
  4. Set Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman.
  5. End your turn.
  6. When your opponent starts their Battle Phase, activate Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman, milling Buster Blader and Destruction Sword Memories to Special Summon Buster Dragon.
  7. When your opponent attacks, activate Linkuriboh's effect to tribute itself.
  8. Activate the previously milled Destruction Sword Memories to Fusion Summon Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman.
Result: Basic Buster Blader lock is set up. Combo #2: Apprentice Illusion Magician & Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman.
  1. Normal Summon Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman.
  2. Use Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman's effect to search Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman.
  3. Special Summon Apprentice Illusion Magician, discarding any card BUT Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman.
  4. Search Dark Magician (not relevant to this combo).
  5. Link Summon Crystron Needlefiber.
  6. Use Crystron Needlefiber's to Special Summon Dragon Buster Destruction Sword from your Deck.
  7. Optional: Link Summon Decode Talker.
  8. Set Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman.
  9. End your Turn.
  10. At any point during your opponent's turn, do the following:
  • Activate Prologue of the Destruction Swordsman, milling Buster Blader and Destruction Sword Memories to Special Summon Buster Dragon.
  • In the same chain, activate Destruction Sword Memories, banishing Buster Whelp of the Destruction Swordsman and Buster Blader to Fusion Summon Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman.
  • Upon resolution of the chain, activate Buster Dragon's effect to equip Dragon Buster Destruction Sword to Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroyer Swordsman.
[Will probably add more later]

deck_name: Level 8 Ritual Kaiju Deck To Make Nobody Like You
deck_excerpt: Get out some lvl 8s or Imp bois, clear problem monsters, dig for Chaos MAX, ???, profit.
deck_description: This is a fairly straightforward deck that I'm trying out for the sake of one of my favorite monsters; Chaos MAX. Kaijus are a fun and incredibly annoying but still entirely viable mechanic that lends itself well to the lvl 8 draw cards, so they were one of the best ways to fit the engine in. The main objective is to take out problematic monsters then beat over the rest of the board, either with your Kaijus or with the main dragon himself, MAX-y boy. Also, I should mention that the extra deck is really random, I just kinda picked usable cards without a whole lot of forethought, but you could fit a couple generic links, a couple lvl 4 overlays and just generally put a bit more effort into it than I initially did. My only regret is that this deck is actually the 4th version of the concept. The first version employed recurring monsters like Grapha to do the deed instead, but my boys in the Dark World just can't keep up anymore. :(  UPDATED FOR IMPCANTATIONS! I, FOR ONE, WELCOME OUR NEW RITUAL OVERLORDS. These little guys help add consistency and a muuuuuuch easier OTK to the deck;  - Summon an Impy-boi in defense position - Creature Swap the Impy-boi away - Summon Chaos MAX - Attack for game  It's freaking hilarious when it goes off.

deck_excerpt: Pure Mekk-Knight Deck 2018
deck_description: After testing this deck time and time again I see that it performs very well and has a low brick rate! You want to go second every duel though if you can, otherwise it is hard to win. To win you need to special summon the Mekk-Knights to OTK your opponent out of nowhere. If you're opponent has one card in a column and you have a spell or trap and a Mekk-Knight in your hand then you should set the spell or trap in the same column as their card(s).  Then you can special summon the Mekk-Knight(s) in the column(s) that have two or more cards! Use Mind Control to take their monsters and link them away with your Mekk-Knights/Scapegoat Tokens.  Final Countdown puts pressure on them as they have to hurry if they want to win while Final Countdown is active. It's a tech choice I came up with that is funny to use. Use Psychokinesis to destroy your opponent's cards and use Psi-Blocker to block their card(s) that you know they are going to try to use. There are other great cards in the deck that have good synergy with the deck like PSY-Framelord Omega. I came up with these great techs that have good synergy with the deck. Hope you all enjoy them and the deck!

deck_excerpt: Trickstar Deck 2018
deck_description: After working with this deck for a while I've finally managed to reach a conclusion on a good Trickstar deck. After testing I've found it has a low brick rate and is extremely competitive for those meta players who are Trickstar fans! The goal of this deck is to burn your opponent every time they draw/search and every time they use a spell/trap. Also, using the Trickstar Reincarnation and Droll & Lock Bird combo to make your opponent lose their entire hand and basically instant lose is amazingly broken and helpful. It's simple, just get two Trickstar Reincarnations using Trickstar Light Stage and Trickstar Candina, then set them. Make sure you have a Droll & Lock Bird in your hand, then once your opponent plays any card on their following turn right after yours, use one of the set Trickstar Reincarnations and right after it resolves and your opponent draws their new hand, start a new chain by activating the other Trickstar Reincarnation, then immediately chain your Droll & Lock Bird in your hand to that Trickstar Reincarnation. Droll & Lock Bird's effect comes first in the chain, therefore it will stop them from searching/drawing anymore this turn, and the Trickstar Reincarnation will set off next, making them banish their entire hand without being able to draw after since Droll & Lock Bird's effect is active. Scapegoat and Eater of Millions are also very powerful tools in this Trickstar build. Use Scapegoat during your opponents end phase allowing you to link summon big boss monsters like Borreload Dragon and Saryuja Skull Dread during your following turn to OTK and overwhelm your opponent.

After his family were sealed into cards by Duel Academy, Kite abandoned the Resistance and began a one-man vendetta against Duel Academy, vowing to seal thousands of its soldiers into cards and earning a bounty on his head as a result. After his Duels against Yuya Sakaki and Shay, Kite has a change of heart and he becomes an ally of the Lancers.

deck_excerpt: A Frog deck based on "Paleozoics", "Frog" summons and "Artifacts" as disruption cards.
deck_description: Characteristics: The main Characteristics of this deck are the typical frog and Paleo plays to get Toadally Awesome on the field. For additional counter plays the deck uses Artifacts to prevent the opponent (or yourself) from banishing cards, prevent extra deck summons or simply destroy cards from your opponent.  Depending on your opponents deck, there are an additional Moralltach and Lancea in the side deck. The Paleozoics are the main traps in this deck and you can use them for your XYZ plays with the frogs.  Additional stuff: Eater of Millions and Sky Cavalry  are used for some protection in case the artifacts brick or when you need to remove a threatening monster. The Handtraps in this deck are Effect Veiler and Artifact Lancea. Ash blossom was to expensive in my opinion so i use effect Veiler as alternative. There are Solemn Warning and Solemn Jufgement in this deck. I didn't include strike to keep the Call of the haunted in the deck But there will be no problems with swapping CotH for some strikes.  Side deck note: Some side deck cards can be swapped out. I have kept Paleozoic Dinomischus because i'm not sure if i should use only 1 copy of that card or 2. I rarely use him but when i use him, he can be helpful. Another card that isn't that important is the Call of the Haunted. I just didn't knew what to include at this point.
