deck_excerpt: Pendulum Magician Deck (Negation + OTK (not Lyrilusc))
deck_description: The goal of this deck is to utilize astrograph sorcerer, chronograph sorcerer, and the likes of the magicians (Wisdom-Eye, Black Fang, Purple Poison, Oafdragon, and Harmonizing) to summon monsters for the LINK Summon of Heavymetalfoes Electrumite (up to 3x on the first turn) --> and to abuse Electrumite to fill the Extra Deck with cards that allow you to make more Electrumites/loop more cards (with astrograph) into the hand. The goal of the Electrumite abuse is to stock the Extra Deck with Pendulum Monsters to bring out a variety of cards (whatever is suitable). With Clear Wing being a board wipe, Starving Venom being an extender (whether that be more negates with Odd-Eyes Vortex, or another card like Electrumite --> which you might want to preserve the effect of for even more looping). The Mythical Beast engine is simply there to speed up the deck (and you include cards, like Rescue Hamster --> which is a tech option in my opinion because it requires cards in the Extra Deck to be of use). If you'd like to see a board with 4+ Negates: Run 2 Starving Venoms, Firewall, Underclock, Norito, and an Odd-Eyes Absolute to pop into a Odd-Eyes Vortex (I don't run this setup but I've seen it, and it works). Other tech options include Psy-Frame, Gameciels (which slow down the deck), Ash or Ghosts (both slow down the deck), and standard side deck cards (for T1 meta like True Draco). This deck is a little more casual than your average Pendulum Mag. build, but it does have an incredible sense of speed --> speed that, if played correctly, can match (if not surpass) many tournament standard decks.

deck_excerpt: Gear up! Spell Shenanigan! In this deck is full of Spells as well as Royal Decree, this is where you dominate your opponent with Spells!
deck_description: In this deck, it requires thinking and strategies to counter your opponent, as well as preparing yourself to protect your field. It is also difficult to sweep a field while also maintaining your resources. Of course, Raigeki is one easy step to clear your opponent's field, but it doesn't necessarily destroyed its spell/traps, which means you'll be opened to any traps/spells your opponent control. In this case, this deck fulfill its its requirements to sweep the field while also maintaining its safety. This deck contains all Strikeblade Archetypes and Spellbook Engine (Spellbook Magician of Prophecy, Spellbook of Secrets, and Spellbook of Knowledges) and Bamboo Sword Engine (Broken Bamboo Sword, Golden Bamboo Sword, and Cursed Bamboo Sword). In fact, it is easy to came across a monster, hopefully any Rei. Strikeblade Maneuver Afterburner, Strikeblade Maneuver Jamming Waves are the card that takes care of both your opponent's monster, traps/Spells. Jamming Waves can take care of any monsters that "cannot be targeted by card effects" since Jamming Waves doesn't specifically say "target". You can use Afterburner to take care of any powerful monsters like Cyber Dragon Infinity (you have to lure it, or to negate it to destroy it). Strikeblade Ignition Engage is the very key to this strategy. If you use it, it is an endless loop of drawing one ~ eight from the deck, while also grabbing three cards from the deck itself, which is extremely consistent. IF you don't have any monster in your hand, or any to draw, go for Strikeblade Battlegear Hornet Bit, then one of the two: Strikeblade Battlegear Widow Anchor or Strikeblade Battlegear Eagle Booster. Also, if you want to refresh Strikeblade Valkyrie Kagari and Strikeblade Valkyrie Shizuku, use Strikeblade Battleship Hercules Base to destroy itself via Strikeblade Battle System Multirole, Strikeblade Airspace Area Zero, or Jamming Waves. You can add Call from the Grave to cancel your opponent's Ash Blossom for easy access. It also is a spell, so it is a great addition to your deck. The only unluckiness in this is when you can't afford to draw a card AND cannot summon a monster. This deck requires a lot of practices, strategies, etc. Anyway, this is all I can give for this week.      " href=""> Strikeblade Airspace Area Zero

deck_excerpt: A very fast near-pure Toon Monsters Deck with great combos based on spellcasters.
deck_description: Great draw power, thanks to 3 Toon Masked Sorcerer, and great search power with Toon Dark Magician, Terraforming, Rapidly swarm monsters, using Summoner Monk, Magician's Circle, Red-Eyes Toon Dragon, Toon Dark Magician, Palladium Oracle Mahad, Toon Mask. Great combos with Magical Dimension/Dark Renewal and Spellcasters, Vengeful Bog Spirit/Soul Exchange and Toon Monsters. Vengeful Bog Spirit shares the Toon Monster handicap to the opponent. Soul Exchange is usable too, because tribute summoned monster (except for Toon Magician Girl) couldn't attack immediately. Comic Hand steal an opponent monster for free, and it could even attack in your very next turn. Magical Dimension is a great opponent's End Phase combo. It has an enormous (ridiculous) staying power thanks to Toon Kingdom, also has great defenses like Mirror Forces, Toon Briefcase, Bottomless, Black Illusion, Compulsory, the Solemn. Even more defenses in the Side Deck, eventually. Some cards like Upstart Goblin and Terraforming are needed because of activation cost and maintenance of Toon Kingdom, as you can see I use 44 cards because of this. You can use another Palladium or Red-Eyes instead of Sorcerer of Dark Magic, it's here only for a "Yugi Deck" factor. In side deck there are some combos too: Toon Defense with Drowning Mirror Force (you should use at least 2 of them for each one and remove all Toon above level 4). Storming Mirror Force is a pain in the ass for the Pendulum/Link Decks and Quaking Mirror Force + Toon direct attacks are the death sentence for old decks.

deck_description: what do: rescue animal/double summon -> dragacius -> pawnch -> darius + another GB (hopefully augustus, which summons another darius from hand) -> dragaycius -> whatever you can make with what's left over (andabatae if possible) The deck "works" because the GB link monster, "drag-uh-kai-ass," sends GBs to the graveyard instead of back to the deck when summoned. You summon him with double-summon, a rescue animal, or whatever you can put on the field, then hit something with him, which should be easy (cant be destroyed by battle while attacking/cards can't be activated until end of damage step) use his effect to summon darius and augustus. On a good day, you will at this point have 5 GBs on the field (augustus, 2 darius, and the 2 GBs that went to the gy to summon dragonkrakkon) use a darius and the GB that THAT darius summoned (if you use the wrong one, the other GB gets shuffled into the deck and then you'll be sad), to reform dragaliscious, then fuse the other three to summon Andabatae, use him to summon gyzarius (pop 2 cards) then fuse those two into tamer editor. If you get to this point, you have options: A: Use editor to summon gyzarius and pop 2 more cards B: Summon Nerokius and xyz into zombiestein->pain gainer->seven sins (or some other rank 8, that one's just one of my favorites) C: Summon heraklinos to lock down your opponent's spells/traps (wrecks house if you happen to also have a facedown war chariot)   problems: If your opponent top decked one of their three ash-blossoms, your day is ruined. If an effect is negated, then you probably have no field, because most of your costs shuffle your field into the deck. usually can't do anything relevant until main phase 2, which means going first is painful. If it bricks, it bricks hard.

deck_excerpt: Destroying meta decks with something old, something new, something borrowed...something blue.
deck_description: This deck take the old combo oriented deck and revamps it by using links allowing it to still put up a strong board. Use it at your leisure. I'm not a fan of the cloud castle/calamities combo but I feel it might be better than twin burst which is why it's there.  Main combos, terraforming into mausoleum if you have 2 tuners in hand, bonus if one of them is Maiden, who summons a blue eyes from deck when targeted by mausoleums effect ,allowing you to go straight into needlefiber.  If you have destrudo, arkbrave or goliath in hand terraform ravine instead. Crystron needlefiber effect to summon o-lion from deck then link into summon sorc, either summon a dragon from hand if none are on field, not recommended but can be useful in certain situations like a matchup vs brandish.  You can easily get dark matter on field into arkbrave goliath combo. From there it's up to you, I don't like bringing out Saryuja unless I need the special summon, the deck for effect is just a bonus.  Enjoy.

deck_excerpt: Pure Spyrals 2018 (Post Banlist)
deck_description: People think Spyrals are dead after the last banlist, but I think otherwise!  Spyrals return in this deck, and only Spyrals! This deck actually did really well in testing and has a pretty low brick rate considering they got hit hard on the last banlist. After days of testing and making this deck from scratch, this is what I came up with for Spyrals for the current 2018 meta format. The goal is to get out Spyral Double Helix using two Spyral monsters, Trigate Wizard, more link monsters, and Spyral Sleeper. Spyral Sleeper is the boss monster of the deck. Summon him by removing from play 3 Spyral cards in your grave. Then equip him with Spyral Gear - Last Resort and use Sleepers effect to target himself and two of your opponents cards for a nasty combo. This deck takes tons of practice so be sure to play it often if you wish to master all the combos and are new to the deck. Or, if you are already a Spyral pro from the previous format then you know the drill. Enjoy!

deck_excerpt: Deck that implements Fusion and XYZ Summoning to overthrow your opponents | Unfinished deck but still usable
deck_description: Use the various Cyber Dragon monsters along with Power Bond to summon the different powerful fusion monsters. Summon out Chimeratech Rampage Dragon to use its effect t0 destroy your opponent's spell & trap cards up to the number of fusion materials used. My strategy is to summon out Rampage Dragon using Power Bond, thus doubling its attack points. Then I use its effect where you send up to two light machine monsters from your deck to the graveyard, and Rampage Dragon gains an additional attack for each monster sent to the graveyard. If you get the right hand you can easily OTK your opponent. One other strategy is to have both Cyber Dragon and Cyber Dragon Drei in your hand. You then special summon Cyber Dragon from your hand while your opponent only controls a monster. Then you normal summon Cyber Dragon Drei which its effect will change all Cyber Dragon monsters on your field to lvl 5 including itself. Then proceed to use those two monsters to XYZ Summon Cyber Dragon Nova, then special summon Cyber Dragon Infinity over Nova. Infinity's effect allows you to turn your opponent's attack position monster into an overlay unit once per turn, which also increases Infinity's attack points by 200 for each overlay unit. You can also use Infinity's effect to turn one of your monsters into an overlay unit for Infinity which will boost its attack points. This deck is still unfinished and being worked on, but it is still usable at its current state. Once it is fully updated I will let everyone know.

I threw Black Luster Soldier in there to since you should be able to summon it easily with Necro Gardna or Kuribandit. It should always be possible to summon Black Rose Dragon or Michael, The Arch-Lightsworn to reset the field or get the upperhand. I've put in Black Rose Dragon since you may not be able to summon Judgment Dragon early into the game or if you got unlucky with your cards in the graveyard.

deck_excerpt: Overpower your opponents using the Rank-Up-Magic cards
deck_description: XYZ Summon Raidraptor - Force Strix, then utilize its effect to add either Raidraptor - Booster Strix or Raidraptor - Necro Vulture to your hand. Booster Strix allows you to destroy you opponent's attacking monster if they attack a Raidraptor monster. Necro Vulture allows you once per turn to tribute a Raidraptor monster to add a Rank-Up-Magic card from your grave to your hand. Use Rank-Up-Magic Skip Force if you have it in your hand to XYZ Summon a Raidraptor monster that is two ranks higher that the one you have on the field already. If you use Necro Vulture's ability to add Skip Force back to your hand, you can rank up your XYZ monster again to gain a very high advantage. This deck as far as I know cannot OTK, but it can severely damage your opponent.

deck_excerpt: A deck focused on Turbo-ing out Blue-Eyes ritual monsters with new cards
deck_description: The strategy of this deck is pretty straight forward, turbo out the 2 Blue-Eyes ritual monsters. This is actually really consistent due to the Deviritual cards, allowing you to easily get both a ritual monster and Advanced Ritual Art/Chaos form. You can also search the ritual monsters with melody of awakening dragon. If you get both rituals out and they have atleast 2 monsters (with 1 of them not being a link monster) you pretty much win since you can switch attack position monsters to defense and reduce their defense to 0, then attack with Chaos MAX and kill them with double piercing damage. Also, you can add any extra deck monsters you want.

deck_excerpt: A basic Malefic deck (Also the Deck Tag says "Stall" but this is actually a beatdown deck)
deck_description: This deck is a "Protect-the-Castle" and beatdown type of deck where you either protect a field spell or the Malefic monsters you control. You can also stop your opponent's monster effects with skill-drain without affecting your own monsters since their only important effect is in the hand. The main field spell of this deck is Mound of the Bound Creator (Not Malefic World) since it protects M-Cyber End and M-Rainbow Dragon, the 2 strongest beat sticks in your deck. I also have some rank 10 plays with Exodius + M-Cyber Dragon/M-Rainbow Dragon

deck_excerpt: 60-card Lightsworn adapted for the Link Format.
deck_description: 1-turn Curious: This requires a bit of luck and planning. But all you need in your starting hand is Trick Clown and Foolish Burial. First, use Foolish to send either Wulf or Felis to the GY. They will then summon themselves. After that, summon Trick Clown, and use Trick and the Lightsworn to summon Minerva. Use Minerva to detach Trick Clown, and hope that you mill Wulf or Felis. After that, use Trick’s effect to revive itself, and use Wulf or Felis (hopefully) to revive themselves, then use all 3 to Link Summon Curious.
